DRAFT Analysis of the GHG Emissions Implications of the Income Mix of New Development

Nathaniel Decker

8/18/2017

Introduction

This is a project undertaken as part of the Data Science for the 21st Century (DS421) National Science Foundation Research Traineeship. Specifically, it is a “Research Experience for Trainees,” a required part of the DS421 program where the trainee contributes to research “outside of their primary discipline” for 50% of a summer. This particular project builds off of work previously performed by the author, Nathaniel Decker, (Decker et al., 2017) and the research sponsor, Christopher Jones (Jones & Kammen, 2014, 2015).

The income of households has a dramatic impact on the effect of geography on households’ greenhouse gas (GHG) footprints (C. Jones & Kammen, 2014). High-income households in dense, accessible neighborhoods have a far lower GHG footprint than high-income households in far-flung exurbs, and this difference is much greater than the difference between low-income households in dense and exurban areas. The actions of local governments have a profound impact on the patterns of new housing construction by the income of the population that moves into the units (Glaeser, Gyourko, & Saks, 2005; Terner Center for Housing Innovation, n.d.). The order-of-magnitude GHG effect of the siting of new housing in California has been shown (Decker et al., 2017; C. Jones & Kammen, 2015), but the extent to which these impacts vary by geographic patterns of the incomes of households that move to those units is unknown. This is an important policy concern because the means of facilitating the development of housing for low- to moderate-income (LMI) families are very different than the means of facilitating the development of market-rate housing.

While the GHG implications of siting LMI housing are extensively debated and have a major role in the funding of LMI housing, the GHG implications of the siting of new market-rate housing have not resulted in major policy changes or new programs. The raison d’etre of the largest state source of affordable housing funding, the Affordable Housing and Sustainable Communities Program, is GHG reduction. The criteria for California awards of the largest federal source of funding for affordable housing construction, the Low Income Housing Tax Credit, have been revised to lower the GHG emissions of these subsidized households. While some state processes to plan for and promote the construction of market rate housing, such as the housing element process, do consider the GHG emissions impact of he siting of new market-rate housing, these measures are largely ineffective (Dillon 2017).

The calculation of the GHG reduction potential stratified by the income of house can be used to understand this pressing policy issue. This calculation should help clarify the GHG emissions payoff of regulatory changes to facilitate market-rate housing generation in infill areas.

Thought Experiment

To estimate how much the income mix of new development matters this analysis takes the form of a thought experiment. Suppose that the next five years of residential development in California follows the geographic patterns of the last five years. Suppose that the income mix of the new residents of the state roughly matches the income mix of the regions of the state they move to. Suppose that the total regional volume of population increase preducted by the state Department of Finance is correct. One of the most important suppositions in this analysis is an attempt to disentangle the two major drivers of household ghg emissions: income and location of residence. This analysis assumes that new households and units in an area roughly mirror the existing residents and units of an area, controlling for income. This means that new market-rate units look roughly-like existing higher-cost units and willbe occupied by moderate-to-high income residents that have roughly the same characterisitics as existing moderate-to-high income residentis in the area. Given these suppositions we consider two scenarios:

  1. Market Rate Infill Scenario: development of infill market-rate housing is facilitated to the point where all market-rate housing is placed in infill areas and income-restricted housing is constructed in farther-flung locations and,

  2. Affordable Infill Scenario: subsidies for income-resticted housing are vastly increased and all of this housing is constructed in infill areas, but no policies are put in place to facilitate the development of new market-rate units in infill areas.

The thought experiment isolates the impact of income mix by geography. It also acknolwedges that, while the affordable housing development system in California creates a system of financing that promotes the GHG-resposible siting of housing, this goal has not yet been actualized in the various systems for market-rate development. While efforts have been made to attempt to push municipalities to adjust their land use regulations to facilitate the GHG-resposible development of new housing supply (particularly the state’s requirements for Regional Housing Needs Allocations (RHNA), Annual Progress Reports (APRs), and housing elements in comprehensive plans), these systems are ineffective.

Results

The California Department of Finance projects that the state will add 1,660,190 new residents in approximately 628,545 households over the next five years. This analysis assumes that this growth will be accomodated with new housing construction and that this volume will roughly follow the regional patterns predicted by the Department of Finance. Within each region the neighborhood patterns of residential construcrtion will reflect the patterns of the past 5 years.

In this thought experiment there is no difference in the location of new development between the two scenarios. The map below shows the similarity between the scenarios. The outlines within the state show the study areas to which households are allocated (these are “public use microdata areas” or “PUMAs” designated by the Census). The orange circles represent the number of new units added to each area. The maps show that the geographic pattern of development is nearly identical in the scenarios. (Though not exactly identical — differences arise because the scenarios place the same number of people in each area. The number of units that this population translates to will vary depending on the income of the new residents.) The same sites are developed in the same cities and suburbs.

The difference comes from the buildings that are developed, and whether the buildings are income-restricted (“affordable”) or not. The maps below show the differences between the scenarios in the San Francisco Bay Area. As in the pervious maps the size of the organge circles indicates the the number of new units developed in each area. The areas are also color-coded to show the average per-household GHG footprint for the relevant income level, with darker blue indicating lower GHG emissions and lighter blue indicating higher per-person GHG footprints. In this scenario the lowest income households are concentrated in the densest, most transit-rich, and lowest GHG-intensive areas of the region: San Francisco, and the central city areas of the other major Bay Area cities: Oakland, Hayward, Richmond, and San Jose. With these infill sites “taken up” by affordable development in this scenario, higher income households are crowded out of the lowest GHG areas of the Bay area and are developed in suburban areas.

The maps above reveal an interesting, but incidental, finding of the analysis — that the GHG intensity of areas when controlled for the income of households varies slightly by income category. The general direction of the impact of income and geogaphy are as expected: central cities tend to have the lowest per-person GHG footprints, while suburban and exurban areas tend to have the highest footprints, and income has a powerful impact on consumption levels which in turn has a big impact on GHG footprints. The general direction of the influence of geography is complicated slightly when considering different income bands. For example, within Marin County the lowest per-person GHG footprints are in the denser areas around San Rafael for the lowest-income households, but the denser areas of Marin actually have slightly higher per-person GHG footprints for higher-income households.
